Here's a test class covering success, failure, and cancellation using modern MSTest v3+ patterns:

```csharp
[TestClass]
public sealed class DataFetcherTests
{
    // Cooperative cancellation: MSTest cancels this token when [Timeout] expires
    public TestContext TestContext { get; set; } = null!;

    [TestMethod]
    [Timeout(5000)]
    public async Task FetchAsync_ReturnsContent_OnSuccess()
    {
        var handler = new MockHandler(new HttpResponseMessage
        {
            StatusCode = HttpStatusCode.OK,
            Content = new StringContent("hello")
        });
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(new HttpClient(handler));

        var result = await fetcher.FetchAsync(
            "https://example.com",
            TestContext.CancellationTokenSource.Token);

        Assert.AreEqual("hello", result);
    }

    [TestMethod]
    [Timeout(5000)]
    public async Task FetchAsync_Throws_OnHttpError()
    {
        var handler = new MockHandler(new HttpResponseMessage
        {
            StatusCode = HttpStatusCode.InternalServerError
        });
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(new HttpClient(handler));

        await Assert.ThrowsExceptionAsync<HttpRequestException>(
            () => fetcher.FetchAsync(
                "https://example.com",
                TestContext.CancellationTokenSource.Token));
    }

    [TestMethod]
    [Timeout(5000)]
    public async Task FetchAsync_Throws_WhenCancelled()
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        cts.Cancel(); // pre-cancel

        var handler = new MockHandler(new HttpResponseMessage(HttpStatusCode.OK));
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(new HttpClient(handler));

        await Assert.ThrowsExceptionAsync<TaskCanceledException>(
            () => fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com", cts.Token));
    }

    // Minimal mock handler — no external mocking library needed
    private sealed class MockHandler(HttpResponseMessage response) : HttpMessageHandler
    {
        protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
            HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
        {
            cancellationToken.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            return Task.FromResult(response);
        }
    }
}
```

**Key patterns shown:**

| Pattern | How |
|---|---|
| **Async tests** | Return `async Task` (never `async void`) |
| **Timeouts** | `[Timeout(ms)]` — MSTest cancels the test if it exceeds the limit |
| **Cooperative cancellation** | `TestContext.CancellationTokenSource.Token` is linked to `[Timeout]`, so your async code exits promptly instead of hanging |
| **Mocking `HttpClient`** | Subclass `HttpMessageHandler` — avoids mocking framework dependencies |
| **Exception assertions** | `Assert.ThrowsExceptionAsync<T>` for async paths |

The critical detail: `TestContext.CancellationTokenSource.Token` is what connects `[Timeout]` to your async code. Without passing it through, a hung `HttpClient` call would block until the timeout kills the thread non-cooperatively.
